00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
CAMERA, OR CINEMATOGRAPHY
AS WE SOMETIMES CALL IT,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
IS A MAJOR ELEMENT IN THE
PRODUCTION OF ALL FILM

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
AND TELEVISION PROGRAMS.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
IT'S WHAT THE CAMERA
CAPTURES SO, ULTIMATELY,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
IT'S WHAT WE SEE
ON OUR SCREEN.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
THERE ARE MANY DIFFERENT
ASPECTS WHICH MAKE UP

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
THIS IMPORTANT FIELD
AND, AS YOU SAW EARLIER,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
LIGHTING IS
JUST ONE OF THEM.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
OTHER AREAS OF CAMERA
INCLUDE FRAMING,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
CAMERA SHOTS, CAMERA
ANGLES, AND MOVEMENT.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
CLASSICALLY - THAT
IS COMMERCIALLY AND

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
TRADITIONALLY -
CINEMATOGRAPHY IS ABOUT

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.000
CAMERA MOVEMENT, ABOUT THE
WAY THAT LIGHT WORKS WITH

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
WHAT THE CAMERA SEES, WE
MIGHT ALSO EXTEND THAT

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
TO ISSUES OF COLOR.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
BUT PRIMARILY I THINK
WE OFTEN THINK ABOUT

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
CINEMATOGRAPHY AND CAMERA
WORK WHEN WE DON'T NOTICE IT

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
- THAT IDEA OF
THE STABLE CAMERA.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
BUT BEYOND THAT AND
PERHAPS MUCH MORE POPULAR

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
THESE DAYS WITH FILMS LIKE
 THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
OR FILMS LIKE WOODY ALLEN'S
 HUSBANDS AND WIVES ,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
THE MOVING CAMERA IS A
REALLY IMPORTANT WAY

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
OF PORTRAYING A SCENE.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
THE FRAMING'S IMPORTANT
BECAUSE IT CONTROLS,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
WITHIN FOUR WALLS, THE
IMAGE FOR THE VIEWER.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
THE FRAMING CONTROLS THE
VANTAGE POINT FROM WHICH

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
THE VIEWER CAN
WATCH THE ACTION.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
THESE INCLUDE FRONT-ON,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.000
FROM BEHIND,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
AND SIDE-ON SHOTS.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
THE FRAMING ALSO CONTROLS
THE ANGLE AT WHICH

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
OBJECTS WITHIN THE
SHOT ARE SHOWN.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
THE ANGLE AT WHICH
SOMETHING IS SHOT

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
CAN GREATLY ALTER
ITS EFFECT.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
FOR INSTANCE, A HIGH
ANGLE SHOT, WHICH

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
INVOLVES SHOOTING
SOMETHING FROM ABOVE,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
CAN MAKE THE SUBJECT
LOOK SMALLER.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
AND A LOW ANGLE SHOT,
WHICH IS SHOT FROM BELOW,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
CAN MAKE THE OBJECT SEEM
LARGER OR MORE POWERFUL

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.000
THAN WHAT THEY ARE.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
AND A DUTCH ANGLE SHOT,OR
DUTCH TILT, WHERE THE

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
CAMERA'S TILTED ON AN
ANGLE, CAN PROVIDE A SENSE

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
OF DISORIENTATION OR
UNEASINESS FOR THE VIEWER.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
FRAMING ALSO CONTROLS THE
SENSE OF DISTANCE BETWEEN

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:51.000
THE VIEWER AND THE
ACTION ON THE SCREEN.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
HERE'S A QUICK RUNDOWN OF
SOME OF THE TYPES OF SHOTS

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
AND THE WAY THEY
CAN BE USED.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
THEY ARE THE EXTREME
LONG-SHOT: USUALLY RESERVED

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
FOR FRAMING LANDSCAPES,
CITIES AND COASTLINES

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
AND IN WHICH THE HUMAN
BODY IS BARELY VISIBLE.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
THE LONG SHOT: IN WHICH
THE HUMAN FIGURES ARE

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
PROMINENT BUT IN WHICH THE
LANDSCAPE STILL DOMINATES.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
THE MEDIUM LONG SHOT:
WHERE PEOPLE CAN BE SEEN

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
FROM ABOUT
THE KNEES UP.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
THE MEDIUM SHOT: IN
WHICH THEY CAN BE SEEN

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
FROM THE WAIST UP.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
THE MEDIUM CLOSE UP:
WHICH FRAMES SOMEONE

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
FROM THE CHEST UP.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
THE CLOSE UP: WHICH
USUALLY FOCUSES ON

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
A FACE OR A
SPECIFIC OBJECT.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
AND THE EXTREME CLOSE
UP: IN WHICH THE FRAMING

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.000
FOCUSES THE VIEWER'S
ATTENTION ON DETAIL.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
REMEMBER THAT THE CONTEXT
OF THE FILM'S NARRATIVE

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
WILL INFLUENCE THE
MEANING THAT IS MADE

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.000
BY THE FRAMING
TECHNIQUES.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
A CLOSE-UP EXCHANGE IN A
ROMANTIC SOAP OPERA

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
WILL SIGNIFY A DIFFERENT
MEANING THAN, SAY,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
THE CLOSE-UP USED IN NEWS
FOOTAGE OF A CONVICTED

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
CON MAN OR A CLOSE-UP
IN A HORROR FILM.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
MORE OFTEN THAN NOT, IT'S
THE CONTEXT OF THE FILM

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
THAT WILL DETERMINE THE
FUNCTION OF THE FRAMING.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
OF COURSE, THESE FEATURES
OF FRAMING ARE A PART OF

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
EVERY FRAMED IMAGE.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
PAINTINGS, PHOTOGRAPHS,
SKETCHES AND CARTOONS

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
ARE ALL FRAMED IN
RELATION TO HEIGHT,

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.000
LEVEL AND DISTANCE.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
SPECIFIC TO FILM AND
TO TELEVISION, HOWEVER,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
IS THE FRAME'S MOBILITY.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
THE FRAME'S MOBILITY
IS USUALLY CALLED

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
"CAMERA MOVEMENT", AND THE
THREE MOST COMMON TYPES

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
OF CAMERA MOVEMENTS
ARE TRACKING SHOTS,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
PANS AND TILTS.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:43.000
(PHONE RINGS)

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:44.000
HELLO.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
HI JUDE, IT'S FRANK.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.000
OH, HI.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
HAVE YOU SEEN MY
 HEADPHONES ANYWHERE?

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
YUP, THEY'RE RIGHT
HERE ON YOUR DESK.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:52.000
I'M LOOKING AT
THEM RIGHT NOW.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
DAMN.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
OKAY, I MIGHT POP IN
 LATER ON TO PICK THEM UP.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
OKAY, BYE.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
A TRACKING SHOT OCCURS
WHEN THE CAMERA TRAVELS

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
IN ONE SMOOTH MOVEMENT
IN ANY DIRECTION -

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:09.000
USUALLY ON A SET OF
TRACKS CALLED A DOLLY.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
ANOTHER COMMON CAMERA
MOVEMENT IS A PAN.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
A PAN GIVES THE IMPRESSION
THAT THE FRAME IS

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
HORIZONTALLY
SCANNING SPACE.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
THIS IS WHERE THE CAMERA
MOVES FROM SIDE TO SIDE

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
FROM A FIXED POSITION.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
THIS TECHNIQUE CAN BE USED
TO GIVE THE IMPRESSION

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
THAT THE CHARACTER
IS SCANNING THE ROOM

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
WITH HIS OR HER EYES.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
A TILT IS A CAMERA
MOVEMENT THAT IS ALSO

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
FROM A FIXED POSITION,
BUT IN THIS CASE

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:47.000
THE CAMERA MOVES
UP OR DOWN.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
THESE MOVEMENTS CAN
HELP THE FILMMAKER DRAW

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:57.000
ATTENTION TO PARTICULAR
OBJECTS IN THE FRAME.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:03.000
(LOUD NOISE)

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:38.000
WHICH BRINGS
US TO EDITING.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
ONCE YOU BECOME
AWARE OF EDITING,

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
IT'S EASY TO NOTICE.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
FILM AND TELEVISION
PROGRAMS RARELY USE ONE

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:47.000
CONTINUOUS SHOT; RATHER,
THEY'RE A SERIES OF SHOTS

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:48.000
STRUNG TOGETHER.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
BUT THE REASON WE
SOMETIMES FORGET

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
ABOUT EDITING IS BECAUSE
MORE OFTEN THAN NOT

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
IT EXISTS AS A
FORM OF DISGUISE.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
THIS IS CALLED
CONTINUITY EDITING.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.000
(SOUND OF SOMEONE
TRYING TO OPEN DOOR)

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
CONTINUITY EDITING
IS VERY IMPORTANT.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.000
IT'S ABOUT RELATING
IMAGES IN A KIND OF

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:12.000
A LOGICAL SEQUENCE.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.000
FOR EXAMPLE, THERE'S
NO POINT CUTTING FROM...

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.000
WE MIGHT START WITH A
CLASSIC ESTABLISHING SHOT

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.000
- THE ESTABLISHING
SHOT OF THE HOUSE.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
NOW IF WE CUT FROM A
HOUSE TO A SPACESHIP,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
THAT'S ILLOGICAL.
WE'RE NOT EXPECTING THAT.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
ACCORDING TO THE PRINCIPLES
OF CONTINUITY EDITING,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
WE WOULDN'T DO
THAT KIND OF EDITING.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:36.000
CONTINUITY EDITING IS
SOMETIMES BROKEN UP,

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.000
THAT PRINCIPLE OF
CONTINUITY IS DESTROYED

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
TO GIVE US AN EFFECT,
PERHAPS TO HEIGHTEN

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
THE IDEA OF UNCERTAINTY,
THE IDEA OF DISCOMFORT

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
IN THE SPECTATOR
WATCHING THE FILM.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
THERE ARE OTHER TECHNIQUES
USED BY FILM EDITORS

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
TO ENSURE CONTINUITY.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.000
THESE INCLUDE THE EYE
LINE MATCH: WHERE WE ARE

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:06.000
SHOWN SOMEONE LOOKING OFF
SCREEN AND THEN SHOWN

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
WHAT IS BEING LOOKED AT.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.000
THE SHOT REVERSE SHOT
PATTERN: WHICH IS COMMONLY

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:14.000
USED IN CONVERSATIONS
BETWEEN CHARACTERS.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
AND THE MATCH ON ACTION:
AN EDITING DEVICE WHERE

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
MOVEMENT IS CARRIED ACROSS
THE BREAK IN THE SHOTS.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
EDITING, THE NARRATIVE,
MISE-EN-SCENE AND

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
CAMERA ANGLES ARE ALL
IMPORTANT ELEMENTS IN

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
UNDERSTANDING THE LANGUAGE
OF FILM AND TELEVISION.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:35.000
(FOOTSTEPS)

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
AND THE GREATER WE
UNDERSTAND THESE ELEMENTS,

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
THE GREATER WE CAN
UNDERSTAND WHAT WE SEE

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:42.000
ON THE SCREEN.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
WHO WAS THAT?

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:39.000
WHO DO YOU
THINK IT WAS?

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.000
I DON'T KNOW,
THAT KILLER DUDE?

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.000
LOOK WHAT HE
DID TO MY CAR!

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:11.000
SO HOPEFULLY THAT GIVES YOU
SOMETHING TO THINK ABOUT

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
- HOW FILM AND TELEVISION'S
UNIQUE LANGUAGE

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:15.000
MAKES MEANING.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:18.000
AND REMEMBER, IF IT'S A
HORROR FILM, YOU PROBABLY

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
HAVEN'T SEEN THE
LAST OF THE KILLER.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:23.000
THEY'RE NOT THAT
EASY TO GET RID OF.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:27.000
FRANK!

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:31.000
SORRY.

